annotation.TEXT: Wall Street financier Michael Milken created the junk bond market in the ‘80s before being charged with racketeering and fraud; he ultimately paid $1.1 billion in restitution and went to prison.
12 Angry Men is a movie about a jury that must decide the fate of a young man accused of killing his father. The cast included Henry Fonda, Lee J. Cobb, and Jack Klugman.
Milk-Bone dog biscuits were originally called Maltoids.
A little of the opening title/chase scene music from the Alfred Hitchcock film North by Northwest.
Radical feminist Andrea Dworkin crusaded against pornography and argued that heterosexual intercourse was used to dominate and humiliate women.
Judd Hirsch is a sad-sack actor best known for playing Alex Rieger on the TV series Taxi.
An imitation of Joel Grey as the Master of Ceremonies in the musical Cabaret.
Destry Rides Again starred Jimmy Stewart as a young sheriff who believes in solving problems without violence, and co-starred Marlene Dietrich as a dance hall girl.
An imitation of Looney Tunes character Hugo the Abominable Snowman, himself a parody of Lennie, the slow-witted farmhand in Steinbeck’s Of Mice and Men.
A paraphrase of the ad campaign for the Slim-Fast diet plan: two delicious Slim-Fast shakes plus a “sensible dinner” every day.
Novelist Gore Vidal admired and wrote about ancient Greece; he also had long-term romantic and sexual relationships with men, although he refused to label himself “gay.”
In The World According to Garp, the Ellen Jamesians are a group of women who have cut out their tongues in tribute to a young rape victim with a similar injury.
The Nutty Professor is a film starring Jerry Lewis as a nerdy, disheveled professor who invents a potion that transforms him into a suave ladies’ man.
A line from the song “I Remember It Well,” from the musical Gigi.
In the late ‘50s, author James A. Michener created a TV show called Adventures in Paradise, about a guy who sails around the South Pacific looking for opportunities to meddle.
The original jingle for Golden Grahams cereal was sung to the tune of “Oh, Dem Golden Slippers,” an old minstrel show song traditionally performed in blackface.
A variant of an old playground taunt: “I see London, I see France. I see [insert name]’s underpants!”
The story of how Lincoln grew his beard on the advice of a little girl is famous. Her name was Grace Bedell. He met her shortly after his inauguration and showed off his whiskers to her.
The owner of the sadly defunct Parthenon restaurant in Chicago, Christos Liakouras, claimed credit for inventing saganaki, or flaming cheese.
James Franciscus appeared in several TV series, including Naked City, Mr. Novak, and Longstreet.
A take on a line from the black comedy Heathers, in which two high school jocks are murdered and left in compromisingly homoerotic circumstances. The actual line: “I love my dead gay son!”
Probably a reference to a 1990 Levi’s 501 ad that featured NYC street drummer Larry Wright, who uses 5-gallon plastic buckets as drums.
Samson is a figure in the Hebrew bible, sort of the Jewish equivalent of Hercules.
“They call me Mr. Tibbs!” is Sidney Poitier’s famous line from the film In the Heat of the Night. The sequel was even titled They Call Me Mister Tibbs!
A line from the theme song to The Brady Bunch, a TV series that revolved around the adventures of a large stepfamily.
“Dodge trucks are ram tough” is an ‘80s ad slogan for the Dodge trucks manufactured by Chrysler.
Weight-loss company Jenny Craig is known for its celebrity spokespersons, including Monica Lewinsky and Queen Latifah.
“Leinie” is a nickname for Leinenkugel beer, from Chippewa Falls, WI.
Mike Brady (played by Robert Reed) was the dad on The Brady Bunch. Gene Hackman was considered for the role but rejected as too inexperienced.
Brought to you by the Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Commando Cody starred in shorts in various episodes during Season 1, starting with MST3K Episode 102, The Robot vs. the Aztec Mummy.
SuperAmerica is a chain of convenience stores located throughout the Upper Midwest. They first opened in St. Paul, MN, in the ‘60s.
A paraphrased line from the famous “To be or not to be” soliloquy in the Shakespeare play Hamlet.
The line “Shane! Come back, Shane!” is uttered by little Joey as Shane (Alan Ladd) rides off at the end of the film.
Aeschylus was an ancient Greek playwright who was allegedly killed when an eagle, mistaking his bald head for a rock, dropped a turtle on him in an attempt to crack open its shell.
B-grade horror films in the ‘50s & ‘60s liked this ending trope, implying more horror was yet to come. Examples: The She Creature, The Blob, The Thing From Another World.
In the so-called “Rodney King Riots” of 1992, violent unrest raged across South Central LA for 6 days after police officers were acquitted in the videotaped beating of a black motorist.
A possible imitation of György Ligeti’s Kyrie (from Requiem), used to announce the presence of the Monolith in 2001: A Space Odyssey.
Puppeteer Bil Baird performed the puppetry for the “Lonely Goatherd” scene in The Sound of Music.
The Playboy Channel is an adult cable channel originally run by men’s mag Playboy, which sold it in 2011.
Hop Sing (played by Victor Sen Yung) was the Chinese cook for the Cartwright family on the TV series Bonanza.
Actor Gavin MacLeod is best known as Captain Merrill Stubing on The Love Boat, but he was also a regular on McHale’s Navy and The Mary Tyler Moore Show.
The bouncing ball to help audiences follow along with song lyrics was invented in the ‘20s by Max Fleischer, for his animated shorts Ko-Ko Song Car-Tunes.
Victory gardens were home gardens of fruits, veggies, and herbs grown during WWI and II to reduce the strain on the nation’s food supply and boost morale.
A reference to MST3K Episode 408, Hercules Unchained.
A line from the song “Wouldn’t It Be Loverly” from the musical My Fair Lady.
Sophocles was a playwright in ancient Greece. Of his 120 plays, only 7 have survived, including Antigone and Oedipus the King.
In the days before 24-hour broadcasting, “WXYZ now concludes its broadcasting day” was a pretty typical station signoff, along with shots of sunsets, rippling flags, etc.
Hercules: Fully annotated by The Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
A possible reference to the label on Dr. Bronner’s Castile Soap, which in addition to Deep Thoughts on about 700 other topics, offers a helpful recipe for a contraceptive douche with this ingredient.
Champion swimmer Esther Williams became an actress when the 1940 Olympics were canceled due to the outbreak of World War II.
Morty Gunty was a comedian who appeared on many TV shows from the ‘50s-‘70s. He played himself in Woody Allen’s Broadway Danny Rose.
A line from the film Blazing Saddles.
Coincidentally, four years after this episode first aired Rip Torn provided the voice of Zeus in the Disney animated feature Hercules.
Operatic soprano Maria Callas was one of the leading performers during the ‘50s and ‘60s.
All people known for their explosions of hair: Reverend Jim Ignatowski was Christopher Lloyd’s character on Taxi. Comedian Tommy Chong was half of the stoner comedy team Cheech & Chong.
Grolsch is a Dutch beer; the brewery was founded in 1615.
Kirby is a brand of vacuum cleaners sold exclusively through in-home demonstrations. Multiple complaints and lawsuits have been filed against its payment and sales practices.
A line from the film Ghostbusters, as Louis Tully (Rick Moranis) attempts to fend off a Devil Dog.
There are pics online of Pete Townshend dressed in drag for a 1986 benefit concert. They are horrifying.
The teen gross-out film Porky’s features a famous scene in which a boy spies on a group of girls taking a shower in a locker room.
Frank Comstock wrote the theme to Rocky and His Friends; he also wrote music for Adam-12, Happy Days, and F-Troop, among others.
Little Big Man is a film about a white man (Dustin Hoffman) raised by the Cheyenne, who winds up at the Battle of Little Bighorn with General Custer.
An imitation of Rip Torn as Artie in The Larry Sanders Show. Artie’s favorite drink was a salty dog, but they tended to make him belligerent.
Romanian musician Gheorghe “Master of the Pan Flute” Zamfir has recorded a number of albums, which were extensively advertised on TV in the ‘80s.
“Stardust” is a 1927 song originally written and recorded by Hoagy Carmichael; it has been recorded more than 1,500 times since then.
Thinsulate is a brand of insulation used in clothing and footwear; it is manufactured by 3M.
Did we miss any references? Be sure to let us know in the comments!
In the first James Bond movie, Dr. No, the villain (played by Joseph Wiseman) is at first filmed so that you cannot see his face, which has since become a cliché.
Finder of Lost Loves was an ‘80s TV show starring Tony Franciosa (not James Franciscus) as a PI specializing in reuniting people with their old flames.
Bobby McFerrin hit it big in 1988 with the song “Don’t Worry, Be Happy.” Fake rumors began circulating as early as 1992 that he had killed himself.
A ‘70s commercial starring Polish actress Rula Lenska used the line “Friends from Europe are here,” later parodied by Jambi on the Pee-wee Herman HBO special.
An imitation of the often-flustered and tongue-tied Woody Allen, the nebbishy comedian/actor/writer/director whose most famous films include Annie Hall and Manhattan.
In the film Caddyshack, when Danny Noonan attempts to sink a putt during a contest, his fellow caddies try to distract him from the sidelines by calling his name.
Actor Alan Alda (Hawkeye Pierce on TV’s M*A*S*H) came to epitomize the sensitive ‘70s male for a lot of people.
“Guns don’t kill people. People kill people” is an unofficial slogan of the National Rifle Association, in use since at least the ‘50s.
Omen III: The Final Conflict starred a young Sam Neill as the Antichrist.
Although many people believe they must receive the Miranda warning when being arrested, in fact police must only read it before questioning a suspect in custody.
“Does this bug you? I’m not touching you” is a frequent MST3K catchphrase, possibly originating in one of Bono’s remarks in the U2 concert film Rattle and Hum.
Comedian Joe Piscopo got into bodybuilding after a diagnosis of thyroid cancer and bulked way up, even hawking dietary supplements for weightlifters in the early ‘90s.
According to the New Testament, Barabbas was the criminal whom the crowd chose to be spared when given a choice to free Barabbas or Jesus.
A line from the classic movie It’s a Wonderful Life.
In Great Britain, a Lido is a swimming pool and facilities, or a part of a beach where swimming is allowed. On a cruise ship, the Lido deck is where the swimming pool etc. is located.
In early 1993, DC Comics, with much fanfare and hoopla, killed off Superman. His death lasted less than a year before they resurrected the character.
Hercules is the Romanized version of our hero’s name; in Greek, it is usually rendered Heracles or Herakles.
A reference to the Star Trek episode “This Side of Paradise,” although the Brains were shocked to discover when they watched it that the line does not actually appear in the episode.
Physicist Stephen Hawking has worked for years with string theory, a popular physics model that is based on string-like objects as the building blocks of the universe.
“Good night and may God bless” was comedian Red Skelton’s trademark closing line on The Red Skelton Show.
Vanquish is an OTC pain reliever that contains both aspirin and acetaminophen. It is manufactured by Strides Pharma.
Grain Belt Premium beer, aka Primo, is a Midwestern brand of beer originally brewed in Minneapolis.
The Blue Lagoon is a film about two children who grow up together on a deserted island, ultimately falling in love and discovering sex.
The Satyricon is a Roman satire written during the reign of Emperor Nero by the respected author Petronius. It is sometimes considered an early precursor of the novel.
Actress Elinor Donahue played elder daughter Betty on the TV show Father Knows Best; she also played pharmacist Ellie Walker on The Andy Griffith Show.
A paraphrase of a line in the Marx Brothers movie Animal Crackers, itself a reference to the experimental Eugene O'Neill play Strange Interlude.
Along with “rutabaga,” “watermelon,” and “peas and carrots,” background extras mutter “rhubarb” to simulate conversation in TV shows and films.
Sparta was an ancient Greek city-state, the chief rival to Athens. Sparta still exists as a city in Greece; about 35,000 people live there.
Getting to Yes is a book on the psychology of negotiation, which teaches people how to bargain and compromise in a non-confrontational way.
Get the inside scoop behind every reference in this epic episode.
Napalm is an incendiary weapon made of jellied gasoline. It became infamous during the Vietnam War, when a picture of a little girl horribly burned by napalm was seen worldwide.
Hector Elizondo is a bearded actor who appeared in every movie directed by Garry Marshall, beginning with Young Doctors in Love.
A line from the song “Bali Ha’i,” from the musical South Pacific.
Actress Mary Martin is best known for her portrayal of Peter Pan in the musical of the same name.
The Dr. Seuss book How the Grinch Stole Christmas! begins with the line, “Every Who down in Whoville liked Christmas a lot.”
“Orange juice: it’s not just for breakfast anymore” is the tag line to a series of ads for Florida oranges that ran during the ‘80s.
The song “Liar” was originally recorded by British rock band Argent, but became a Top 10 hit for American band Three Dog Night.
The original Gilligan’s Island led to two animated sequel series and three reunion films (including the improbable The Harlem Globetrotters on Gilligan’s Island).
A line from “Drivin’ My Life Away,” one of Eddie Rabbitt’s biggest hits.
Minibikes are a kind of smallish motorcycle that became popular in the ‘60s & ‘70s. Rupp was a popular brand now considered a collectible.
“Yakety Sax” by Boots Randolph was often used during sped-up chases on the British skit comedy show The Benny Hill Show.
Roy Rogers was a singer and actor who starred in a vast succession of Westerns from the ‘30s-‘50s, including an eponymous TV show.
A paraphrased line from the classic British TV show Fawlty Towers, spoken by John Cleese as hotel owner Basil Fawlty.
A line from the John Denver song “Follow Me.” Denver said he wrote it for his wife, Annie; early in his career the two were often separated while he was touring.
Despite the title, nearly all the dinosaur species featured in the film Jurassic Park lived during the Cretaceous period.
An imitation of Flash Bazbo, Space Explorer, a recurring character voiced by Christopher Guest on The National Lampoon Radio Hour, which aired weekly in 1974.
Baywatch was actually canceled due to low ratings after its first season; star David Hasselhoff brought it back in syndication to tremendous success.
Because the character of Bozo the Clown was franchised out to local markets, many different actors played the part, including Today Show weatherman Willard Scott.
Congress has had gobs of sex scandals, but the ongoing one when this aired was Sen. Bob Packwood, who resigned after more than 2 dozen women accused him of sexual misconduct.
A reference to MST3K Episode 422, The Day the Earth Froze.
A 1996 Beck’s beer ad showed ships sailing and suns setting and people enjoying good, wholesome beer, to the strains of “Sail Away” by German rocker Hans Hartz.
On the TV series The Millionaire, an eccentric rich man would send random people a check for $1 million. You never saw his face, only the back of his head and sometimes his arm and hand.
A Pampers ad campaign in the ‘80s expressed sympathy for any baby stuck in “a saggy diaper that leaks.”
Silly String has been used by the U.S. military in Iraq to test for hidden tripwires.
Let us know if we missed any references!
Thanks for watching this fully-annotated presentation of Hercules!
A line from The Wizard of Oz.
An imitation of cartoon character Popeye the Sailor Man’s typically scattered mutterings.
Originally, the sculptures at Mt. Rushmore were to feature the presidents from head to waist, but the project ran out of funding.
The athletic teams of Ohio State University are all called Ohio State Buckeyes. The mascot is Brutus Buckeye, a man with a horse chestnut for a head.
Joan Embery, the “Goodwill Ambassador” for the San Diego Zoo, appeared on numerous TV shows in the ‘70s-‘80s, along with various zoo animals.
Falling off the pier; crashing into its pilings; terrorists blowing up the pier while the governor speaks—these were the everyday problems facing the lifeguards of Baywatch.
A line from the Tom Jones song “What’s New Pussycat?” It was written as the theme song for a Peter Sellers film, but has become much more famous than the movie.
With annotations provided by The Annotated MST website.
Lassie was originally played by a male collie named Pal; Pal’s descendants continue to play Lassie to this day.
An imitation of Dr. Zachary Smith (Jonathan Harris), the villain/comic relief from the campy TV sci-fi series Lost in Space.
“Missed me, missed me, now you gotta kiss me” is an old playground taunt.
A famous c. 1980 ad campaign for Irish Spring soap featured an Irishwoman delivering the line “Manly, yes, but I like it too”—referring to its traditionally masculine scent.
C&H sugar ads using this jingle in the ‘70s and ‘80s tended to use lush Hawaiian scenery as a backdrop.
The inventor of 2000 Flushes, Al Eisen, claims he came up with it just to get out of cleaning the toilet.
The Fontainebleau Hotel is a luxury hotel in Miami Beach, Florida.
A weed whipper is a gardening device that cuts grass and weeds with a whirling length of string, usually a plastic line.
In the ‘80s, media mogul Ted Turner announced controversial plans to add color to classic black-and-white films, including Citizen Kane.
An imitation of Michael Palin on an episode of Monty Python in which he played Ron Higgins, a professional impersonator of French clergyman Cardinal Richelieu.
Rod McKuen was an immensely popular poet during the ‘60s. Critics called him simplistic and sentimental, but he remained a guru to the flower child generation.
Swiss Family Robinson is a 19th-century novel about a shipwrecked family. Animals on the island ranged improbably from moose to kangaroos to rhinos.
In Greek mythology, the bull Taurus was actually the god Zeus in disguise, out to seduce one in a very lengthy series of maidens.
The theme song for The Rocky and Bullwinkle Show, aka Rocky and His Friends.
The Naked Prey is a film about a group on safari in Africa who run afoul of a local tribe. The sole survivor, pursued by tribesmen, becomes the huntee rather than the hunter.
“It was a dark and stormy night,” known as the epitome of clichéd writing, is the opening line to the 1830 novel Paul Clifford by Edward Bulwer-Lytton.
Jack Nicholson’s famous line from the film A Few Good Men.
Manwich is a brand of canned sloppy joe sauce made famous by the ‘70s slogan “A sandwich is a sandwich but a Manwich is a meal.”
An imitation of Jackie Gleason as his character Reginald Van Gleason III.
Alice Cooper’s music video for “School’s Out” had Cooper dancing with “Muppets” in front of a wrecked classical temple.
The famous ad jingle for Oscar Mayer bologna was written by Richard Trentlage for a contest and sung by his kids; it debuted in 1963 and ran for 47 years.
Cindy Lou Who almost foils the Grinch’s plans when she toddles sleepily out of bed. In the TV special she was voiced by June “Rocky the Squirrel” Foray.
Fingerhut is a direct-sales company (catalogs, website, etc.) based in Minnetonka, MN.
“If I have only one life to live, let me live it as a blonde” is a line from a Clairol ad from the ‘60s.
Malcolm X was a radical black leader during the ‘60s who preached racial pride and black separatism, as opposed to leaders like MLK, who wanted greater integration.
Clay Shaw was a New Orleans businessman who was accused by DA Jim Garrison of conspiring with the CIA to assassinate JFK; he was acquitted by a jury.
An imitation of French ocean explorer Jacques Cousteau. Albert Falco was the chief diver aboard Cousteau’s boat, the Calypso.
My Friend Flicka is a novel about a boy and his horse. It was made into a movie starring Roddy McDowall in 1943.
A line from the Carole King song “I Feel the Earth Move.” It was one of the biggest hits of 1971, spending 5 weeks at #1.
This is a jingle from a series of ads for Taster’s Choice coffee that ran during the ‘80s.
A line from an ‘80s ad for Kibbles ’n Bits dog food.
Percy Faith was a bandleader known for his lush orchestral arrangements. He was an early pioneer of the easy listening genre.
St. Pauli Girl is a brand of German beer. Its name comes from the former St. Paul’s Friary located next door to the original brewery.
The video for Aerosmith’s song “Love in an Elevator” opens with a young woman greeting singer Steven Tyler as he enters an elevator with “Oh, good morning, Mr. Tyler. Going … down?”
Pop artist Jim Dine is known for attaching everyday objects, such as saws, axes, and scissors, to his sculptures.
Actor/singer Gordon MacRae played the lead in two classic Rodgers & Hammerstein film musicals: Curly in Oklahoma! and Billy Bigelow in Carousel.
In Woody Allen’s film Everything You Always Wanted to Know About Sex* (*But Were Afraid to Ask), Gene Wilder played a doctor who falls in love with a sheep.
In the ‘90s, Pace picante sauce ran ads with cowpokes horrified to discover their camp cook is using a salsa that is (unlike Pace) made in New York City.
In the 1981 film Arthur, Arthur’s valet Hobson responds to his announcement that he’s going to take a bath with an acerbic “I’ll alert the media.”
Of the 70K American and Filipino POWs who set out on the Bataan Death March in WWII, only 54K arrived; the rest died on the way or escaped into the jungle.
In the film The Sound of Music, the children accompany the song “So Long, Farewell” with big sweeping waves of their arms.
A reference to a series of Ford ads, in which they would say, “Remember, use only genuine Ford brand parts!”
One of the reasons Skipper puts up with Gilligan’s annoying behavior on Gilligan’s Island: Gilligan saved his life in the war (which war is unspecified).
Solid Gold was a syndicated TV show in the ‘80s in which dancers writhed to top 10 hits. Several of them went on to middling acting careers (e.g., Lucinda Dickey and Chelsea Field).
A paraphrase of the song “Sylvia’s Mother” by Dr. Hook & the Medicine Show: “Sylvia’s mother says Sylvia’s busy, too busy to come to the phone.”
Dennis Day was an Irish-American singer who frequently appeared on Jack Benny’s show. He briefly had his own TV series in the ‘50s, The Dennis Day Show.
And now, we invite you to enjoy…the fully-annotated Hercules!
Other Diet Coke slogans throughout the years: “You are what you drink,” “Hello you …” and “I light it.”
A reference to the scene in The Wizard of Oz where Dorothy and her friends are overcome by a field of poppies.
World champion gymnast Kurt Thomas made the wonderfully bad movie Gymkata in 1985, in which he defeats the bad guys with the help of randomly placed gymnastics equipment.
The French cognac Rémy Martin has been bottled since 1724.
"It ain’t over till it’s over” is a famous line by baseball manager Yogi Berra, said about the 1973 National League pennant race. (He won.)
Actress Bea Arthur was famous for her flowing tunics and caftans on the ‘90s TV series The Golden Girls.
A paraphrase of a line from the Mike Douglas song “The Men in My Little Girl’s Life.”
A take on a Groucho Marx line from the Marx Brothers movie A Day at the Races: “Either he’s dead or my watch has stopped.”
“Taste it all” was an ad slogan for Diet Coke in 1993.
Sensurround was a gimmick to lure audiences into theaters. It was used to hype the 1974 film Earthquake by promising to use low-frequency sound to literally shake the audience.
“You must go on. I can’t go on. I’ll go on” is a line from the novel The Unnamable by Samuel Beckett.
A reference to the Cowardly Lion from The Wizard of Oz.
Eddie Rabbitt was a popular country/crossover singer in the ‘70s and ‘80s. He died young from lung cancer in 1998.
Did we somehow miss a reference? Drop us a line in the comments!
Actor Bert Lahr was best known for playing the Cowardly Lion in The Wizard of Oz.
The Punt, Pass & Kick competition is held by the NFL for boys and girls ages 6-15, to test their skills in various aspects of football.
ComfoRest was a brand of adjustable mattresses made by a now-defunct Minneapolis-based company.
This line was frequently used in station promos for the cable sports channel.
The founder of Trojan condoms made his product respectable by marketing it exclusively to pharmacists rather than consumers.
An imitation of the typically lustful way Bob Hope would talk about his voluptuous co-stars.
The Land Before Time is an animated film about an orphaned Apatosaurus on a quest for a new home; it spawned 13 direct-to-video sequels.
